#### **Quality**

As I mentioned at the beginning of this series, 80% quality was sufficient for my purposes, as I always planned to include a layer of manual review.

Quality breaks down into three aspects, as the automation performed with varying levels of success across each:

* **Relevance**: How many irrelevant news items were picked up, and how many relevant ones were missed?  
* **Accuracy**: How accurate was the information extracted from the articles?  
* **Duplicate removal**: How many duplicate articles were incorrectly classified as new, or vice versa?

Quick note: the total numbers vary slightly across metrics because I refined AI prompts during testing. The figures below reflect the final version I kept.

#### ***Relevance***

Of the 72 news items the automation classified as relevant, I deemed 18 (25%) to be irrelevant or only loosely relevant. While this is slightly higher than my initial 20% threshold, around 7 of those articles fell into a grey area. They covered pharma or biotech announcements involving cash injection, such as partnerships, acquisitions, or awards, but were not explicit private or public funding rounds.

Since I didn't explicitly exclude these in my prompt, they're arguably still relevant depending on your use case. If we treat them as such, then only 11 news items (15%) were falsely classified as relevant.

More importantly, the automation rarely missed relevant news. Of the 194 news items processed, only 3 relevant ones (1.5%) were missed. After further investigation, these were actually classified as relevant but were mistakenly removed during duplicate detection, which led to adjustments to that prompt.

The key takeaway here is that while the automation slightly over-includes, which is easy to fix during manual review, it is very robust when it comes to not missing important funding updates. Missing relevant news would have been far more time-consuming to identify manually.

Overall, this comfortably meets my 80% quality threshold and could be further improved with more detailed prompting.

#### ***Accuracy***

Of the 82 news items summarised, only 4 (\~5%) contained errors, with 2 items (2%) not being real, likely due to AI hallucination. Fortunately, these errors were easy to spot: missing headlines or links, or mismatches between headlines and link previews. These would have been removed during manual review.

Two important notes here. First, I explicitly asked in my prompt for all details to be extracted only from the article itself. If specific information was not mentioned in that article, it was marked as ‚ÄúN/A‚Äù, even if other publications covering the same news included those details. Additionally, if an article was behind a paywall, only the available preview was used.

You could remove this constraint, but expect more hallucinations unless you use advanced models or add internet search capabilities.

Second, using Jina AI with API keys allowed me to scrape the vast majority of websites. However, on rare occasions, only 3 times out of 194 news items, I encountered the error below:

The most likely explanation is that the website blocked Jina AI, which is common for sites with more sophisticated anti-bot measures. Since this happened infrequently and did not interrupt the workflow, I did not attempt to fix it. For more complex scraping needs, Apify agents might be a better alternative.

#### ***Duplicate Removal***

This was briefly covered last week, but for completeness, of the 83 news items reviewed, only 4 (\~5%) duplicates were included. After the latest review, I added a few extra conditions to the duplicate removal prompt to prevent false positives, but the core logic remained unchanged, as overall performance was already strong.

**Bottom line:** The automation met my 80% quality requirement across relevance, accuracy, and duplicate removal. Further improvements are possible, but the current performance is more than sufficient for practical use.

Assessing ongoing maintenance time is more difficult. Updates to LLMs, changes to Zapier modules, or shifts in Jina AI‚Äôs offerings could all increase maintenance requirements, and in some cases might require a partial or full rebuild.

That said, over the short testing period, the only meaningful changes I made were prompt adjustments based on quality reviews. Diagnosing and refining the Gemini instructions took approximately 4 additional hours over two weeks, bringing the total time investment to \~**25 hours**.

Early on, manual review took 30-40 minutes/day, as I often had to open and read articles myself. After the prompt improvements, review time dropped to \~5-10 minutes/day, depending on news volume. Assuming a five-day work week, that means manual review now takes **no more than 1 hour/week**.

For comparison, performing a similar task manually used to take me 6-7 hours/week. Most of that time was spent determining relevance when headlines were unclear and extracting key information from articles.

One caveat is that when working manually, I would sometimes conduct additional searches to fill in missing details. The current automation does not do this, although it could be extended to include that functionality.

#### ***Company-Level Impact***

At first glance, saving around ¬£4k/year per role might not sound transformative. Salaries still need to be paid, after all. But this changes once we zoom out.

Let‚Äôs assume Savvy Consulting has 50 employees, with around 10 people contributing to Google Alerts tasks weekly, at a blended rate of ¬£15/hour.

**Bottom line:** The biggest financial impact comes from released capacity, enabling additional billable work without increasing headcount.
